mitre_attack_techniques.signature_description: Adversaries may use rootkits to hide the presence of programs, files, network connections, services, drivers, and other system components.
Adversaries may use bootkits to persist on systems.
Adversaries may maliciously modify components of a victim environment in order to hinder or disable defensive mechanisms.
Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools.
Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.
Adversaries may modify file time attributes to hide new or changes to existing files.
Adversaries may delete or modify artifacts generated within systems to remove evidence of their presence or hinder defenses.
Adversaries may abuse Pre-OS Boot mechanisms as a way to establish persistence on a system.
Adversaries may modify and/or disable security tools to avoid possible detection of their malware/tools and activities.
An adversary may steal web application or service session cookies and use them to gain access to web applications or Internet services as an authenticated user without needing credentials.
An adversary may attempt to get detailed information about the operating system and hardware, including version, patches, hotfixes, service packs, and architecture.
Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
Adversaries may employ a known encryption algorithm to conceal command and control traffic rather than relying on any inherent protections provided by a communication protocol.
Adversaries may interact with the native OS application programming interface (API) to execute behaviors.
Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries.
Adversaries may leverage the resources of co-opted systems in order to solve resource intensive problems, which may impact system and/or hosted service availability.
Adversaries may destroy data and files on specific systems or in large numbers on a network to interrupt availability to systems, services, and network resources.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Suspicious Network Connection to IP Lookup Service APIs
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects external IP address lookups by non-browser processes via services such as "api.ipify.org". This could be indicative of potential post compromise internet test activity.
Detects specific process parameters as used by ACTINIUM scheduled task persistence creation.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Windows Shell/Scripting Processes Spawning Suspicious Programs
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects suspicious child processes of a Windows shell and scripting processes such as wscript, rundll32, powershell, mshta...etc.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Suspicious Command Patterns In Scheduled Task Creation
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects scheduled task creation using "schtasks" that contain potentially suspicious or uncommon commands

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Suspicious DotNET CLR Usage Log Artifact
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the creation of Usage Log files by the CLR (clr.dll). These files are named after the executing process once the assembly is finished executing for the first time in the (user) session context.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Suspicious DNS Query for IP Lookup Service APIs
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects DNS queries for IP lookup services such as "api.ipify.org" originating from a non browser process.
Detects a rundll32 that communicates with public IP addresses

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Potentially Suspicious WDAC Policy File Creation
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects suspicious Windows Defender Application Control (WDAC) policy file creation from abnormal processes that could be abused by attacker to block EDR/AV components while allowing their own malicious code to run on the system.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Unsigned DLL Loaded by Windows Utility
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects windows utilities loading an unsigned or untrusted DLL.
Adversaries often abuse those programs to proxy execution of malicious code.
